    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is a healthy body fat percentage?</summary>
        <p>For men, a healthy range is generally 14-24%, with 6-13% considered athletic and 18-24% average. For women, a healthy range is 21-31%, with 14-20% athletic and 25-31% average. These ranges increase slightly with age. Body fat below essential levels (under 5% for men, under 13% for women) is dangerous and can cause serious health problems including hormonal disruption and immune suppression. Use our <a href="/health-calculators/body-fat-calculator/">body fat calculator</a> to estimate your current percentage.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How accurate are body fat scales?</summary>
        <p>Consumer body fat scales use bioelectrical impedance analysis (BIA) and are typically accurate to within 3-8% of your actual body fat. Results are heavily influenced by hydration levels, recent meals, recent exercise, and even skin temperature. A single reading should not be taken as your definitive body fat percentage. However, if you measure under the same conditions consistently (same time each day, before eating), the trend over weeks and months will be reliable even if the absolute number is off.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is body fat percentage better than BMI?</summary>
        <p>For most individuals, yes. Body fat percentage directly measures what actually affects health: the ratio of fat to lean tissue. BMI cannot distinguish between muscle and fat, which means it can misclassify muscular people as overweight and fail to identify "skinny fat" individuals with normal weight but high body fat. However, BMI remains useful as a free, instant screening tool, especially for sedentary populations. For the most complete picture, use both. Check your <a href="/health-calculators/bmi-calculator/">BMI</a> and your <a href="/health-calculators/body-fat-calculator/">body fat percentage</a>.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do I measure body fat at home?</summary>
        <p>Two practical options are available. First, a consumer body fat scale (BIA device), which you can purchase for $25 to $100, provides a quick estimate when used under consistent conditions. Second, the Navy body fat method requires only a tape measure: measure your neck, waist, and (for women) hips, then plug the numbers into our <a href="/health-calculators/body-fat-calculator/">body fat calculator</a>. Neither method is highly precise, but both are useful for tracking changes over time when measured consistently.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How fast can I safely lose body fat?</summary>
        <p>A safe and sustainable rate is 0.5 to 1 pound of fat per week, which translates to roughly 0.5-1% body fat per month. This requires a moderate calorie deficit of 300-500 calories per day combined with resistance training to preserve muscle mass. Faster fat loss typically results in significant muscle loss, metabolic slowdown, and nutritional deficiencies. Use our <a href="/health-calculators/tdee-calculator/">TDEE calculator</a> to find your maintenance calories, then subtract 300-500 calories to find your target for safe fat loss.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

